abstract: New York Times Co is expected to name company insider Meredith Kopit Levien as its next chief executive officer to succeed Mark Thompson, Bloomberg News reported https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-21/new-york-times-poised-to-name-meredith-kopit-levien-as-next-ceo on Friday, citing people familiar with the matter.
snippet: New York Times Co is expected to name company insider Meredith Kopit Levien as its next chief executive officer to succeed Mark Thompson, Bloomberg News reported https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-21/new-york-times-poised-to-name-mere...
lead_paragraph: (Reuters) - New York Times Co is expected to name company insider Meredith Kopit Levien as its next chief executive officer to succeed Mark Thompson, Bloomberg News reported https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-21/new-york-times-poised-to-name-meredith-kopit-levien-as-next-ceo on Friday, citing people familiar with the matter.
headline_main: New York Times Plans to Name Meredith Kopit Levien as Next CEO: Bloomberg News
headline_print_headline: New York Times Plans to Name Meredith Kopit Levien as Next CEO: Bloomberg News

abstract: Democratic presidential candidate Pete Buttigieg says he needs to raise $13 million to stay competitive through the 14-state Super Tuesday contests on March 3, despite strong finishes in the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary.
snippet: Democratic presidential candidate Pete Buttigieg says he needs to raise $13 million to stay competitive through the 14-state Super Tuesday contests on March 3, despite strong finishes in the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES, Iowa — Democratic presidential candidate Pete Buttigieg says he needs to raise $13 million to stay competitive through the 14-state Super Tuesday contests on March 3, despite strong finishes in the Iowa caucuses and New Hampshire primary.
headline_main: Despite Strong Start, Buttigieg Seeks $13 Million for Mar. 3
headline_print_headline: Despite Strong Start, Buttigieg Seeks $13 Million for Mar. 3

abstract: The corporate home of The New Yorker, which reported on Harvey Weinstein and others who have used nondisclosure agreements to silence accusers, steps back from a common settlement tactic.
snippet: The corporate home of The New Yorker, which reported on Harvey Weinstein and others who have used nondisclosure agreements to silence accusers, steps back from a common settlement tactic.
lead_paragraph: Condé Nast, the publishing giant behind Vogue, The New Yorker and Vanity Fair, said on Friday that it would no longer use nondisclosure agreements for matters involving harassment and discrimination.

lead_paragraph: I’ll let you in on a little secret about media coverage of prime-time political debates: What happens in the first half, even the first quarter, gets much more attention than what happens as the night drags on.

headline_main: Why Democrats Are Bound for Disaster

abstract: Michael R. Bloomberg, who was challenged at this week’s Democratic debate over the agreements, said the women had made complaints “about comments they said I had made.” His rivals said it wasn’t enough.
snippet: Michael R. Bloomberg, who was challenged at this week’s Democratic debate over the agreements, said the women had made complaints “about comments they said I had made.” His rivals said it wasn’t enough.
lead_paragraph: LAS VEGAS — Michael R. Bloomberg said Friday that he was willing to release three women from nondisclosure agreements with his company so they could discuss their complaints about him publicly, reversing himself from his position at this week’s Democratic presidential debate when he came under fire from his rivals for resisting such a move.

abstract: The state’s contest will be the first this presidential cycle in which the racial makeup comes close to reflecting the nation’s population as a whole.
snippet: The state’s contest will be the first this presidential cycle in which the racial makeup comes close to reflecting the nation’s population as a whole.
lead_paragraph: The Nevada caucuses on Saturday will be the first contest of the Democratic presidential race with a racial makeup that (very roughly) reflects the population of the nation as a whole.

abstract: Democratic voters feel generally positive about all of their top candidates running for president, but they have only moderate confidence that their party’s nomination process is fair, according to a new poll by The Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research.
snippet: Democratic voters feel generally positive about all of their top candidates running for president, but they have only moderate confidence that their party’s nomination process is fair, according to a new poll by The Associated Press-NORC Center fo...
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Democratic voters feel generally positive about all of their top candidates running for president, but they have only moderate confidence that their party’s nomination process is fair, according to a new poll by The Associated Press-NORC Center for Public Affairs Research.
headline_main: AP-NORC Poll: Democrats Feel Mixed About Nomination Process
